
  I've fully implemented the Typed Request/Response Objects pattern for the Events domain as a reference implementation.

  What Was Created

  1. New Request Types (core/models/event/event_request.py):

  | Request Type              | Purpose                    | Fields                                        |
  |---------------------------|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
  | EventStatusUpdateRequest  | Update event status        | event_uid, status, notes, cancellation_reason |
  | CheckConflictsRequest     | Check conflicts            | event_uid                                     |
  | RecurringInstancesRequest | Create recurring instances | event_uid, count                              |
  | GetRecurringEventsRequest | Get recurring events       | user_uid, limit                               |
  | AddAttendeeRequest        | Add attendee               | event_uid, user_uid, role, send_notification  |
  | RemoveAttendeeRequest     | Remove attendee            | event_uid, user_uid, send_notification        |
  | CalendarEventsRequest     | Get calendar events        | user_uid, start_date, end_date, limit         |
  | EventHistoryRequest       | Get event history          | user_uid, days_back, limit                    |
  | EventsInRangeRequest      | Get events in range        | start_date, end_date, user_uid, limit         |

  2. Updated Service Methods (core/services/events_service.py):

  # Before (positional args - fragile)
  async def update_event_status(self, event_uid: str, status: str) -> Result[Event]:

  # After (typed request - safe)
  async def update_event_status(self, request: EventStatusUpdateRequest) -> Result[Event]:

  3. Updated Routes (adapters/inbound/events_api.py):

  # Before (manual extraction)
  uid = request.path_params["uid"]
  body = await request.json()
  return await events_service.update_event_status(uid, data.status)

  # After (typed request object)
  typed_request = EventStatusUpdateRequest(
      event_uid=uid,
      status=body.get("status"),
      notes=body.get("notes"),
      cancellation_reason=body.get("cancellation_reason"),
  )
  return await events_service.update_event_status(typed_request)

  Benefits of This Pattern

  1. No More Lost Data: The notes and role parameters that were being dropped are now preserved
  2. Compile-Time Safety: MyPy verifies all fields are correct at the boundary
  3. Self-Documenting: Request objects show exactly what data each operation needs
  4. Refactoring-Safe: Change the request dataclass, MyPy tells you every call site to update
  5. Validation at Boundary: Pydantic validates all fields at API entry, before service logic runs

  Pattern for Other Domains

  To apply this pattern to other domains:

  1. Create request types in core/models/{domain}/{domain}_request.py
  2. Update service methods to accept typed request objects
  3. Update routes to construct request objects from HTTP data
  4. Run MyPy to verify type safety
